definitions: person or company hired by a main contractor to complete specialized work
examples: The general contractor hired a subcontractor to install the plumbing system
Several subcontractors worked together to finish the office building renovation

definitions: distinct social group within larger culture sharing unique beliefs and practices
examples: The punk subculture emerged in the 1970s with distinctive music and fashion
Online gaming has created its own subculture with specialized language and customs

definitions: housing development created by dividing larger land into smaller lots
process of dividing something into smaller parts or sections
examples: They bought a house in the new subdivision near the elementary school
The neighborhood subdivision has strict rules about lawn maintenance and house colors
The subdivision of the property required approval from the planning commission
Further subdivision of the department would create too many small units

definitions: taxonomic category in biology ranking below family and above genus
examples: Lions belong to the Pantherinae subfamily within the cat family
The subfamily includes several related genera with similar characteristics

definitions: distinct section within larger group sharing specific characteristics or purposes
examples: The research team formed a subgroup to focus on data analysis
Each subgroup in the committee addressed different aspects of the proposal

definitions: condition of being under control or domination of another person or force
examples: The country endured years of subjection under foreign rule
His subjection to constant criticism affected his self-confidence deeply

definitions: quality of being based on personal feelings opinions or experiences rather than facts
examples: The subjectivity of art criticism makes it impossible to define absolute standards
We must acknowledge the subjectivity inherent in all historical accounts

definitions: process of bringing under complete control through force or intimidation
examples: The subjugation of indigenous peoples left lasting scars on their cultures
Economic subjugation can be as effective as military conquest

definitions: property or part of property rented by tenant to another person
examples: She found a sublet for the summer while the regular tenant traveled
The apartment sublet included all utilities and furnished rooms

definitions: transformation of unacceptable impulses into socially acceptable activities in psychology
direct transition of substance from solid to gas without becoming liquid
examples: Artists often use sublimation to channel intense emotions into creative works
Through sublimation he transformed his anger into motivation for charity work
Dry ice undergoes sublimation at room temperature turning directly into carbon dioxide gas
The sublimation of snow in cold dry conditions creates interesting weather patterns

definitions: watercraft designed to operate underwater for military or research purposes
examples: The submarine stayed submerged for three weeks during the mission
Nuclear submarines can remain underwater for months without surfacing

definitions: condition of being completely covered or hidden beneath water or liquid
examples: The prolonged submergence damaged the electronic equipment beyond repair
Complete submergence of the plants will kill them within days

definitions: process of putting or going under water or beneath a surface
examples: The submerging of the artifact in preservation fluid took careful planning
Submerging yourself in cold water can reduce inflammation after exercise

definitions: small underwater craft designed for deep sea exploration and research
examples: The submersible descended to explore the ocean floor near volcanic vents
Scientists used a remote-controlled submersible to study deep sea creatures

definitions: act or state of being put completely under water or other liquid
examples: Total submersion in the language helped her become fluent quickly
The submersion therapy required holding his breath for extended periods

definitions: formal presentation of document proposal or application for consideration
act of accepting authority or surrendering to superior force
examples: The deadline for manuscript submission is next Friday at midnight
Her submission to the competition included detailed architectural drawings
His submission to the new regulations came after months of resistance
The dog showed submission by lowering its head and tail

definitions: person who works under supervision of someone in higher position
examples: The manager held weekly meetings with all her subordinates
Good leaders know how to motivate and support their subordinates

definitions: arrangement where one element is placed under control or authority of another
examples: The subordination of personal interests to team goals improved overall performance
Grammatical subordination connects clauses to show their relationship

definitions: written legal order requiring person to appear in court or provide evidence
examples: The witness received a subpoena to testify at the trial next month
Ignoring a subpoena can result in contempt of court charges

definitions: distinct group within larger population sharing specific characteristics for research purposes
examples: Researchers studied a subpopulation of elderly patients with diabetes
This subpopulation shows different voting patterns than the general public

definitions: set of computer instructions designed to perform specific task within larger program
examples: The programmer wrote a subroutine to handle error messages efficiently
Each subroutine in the code performs one clearly defined function

definitions: person who pays to receive regular service publication or digital content
examples: The magazine has over fifty thousand subscribers worldwide
New subscribers get a discount for their first three months

definitions: character or symbol written below normal line of text in mathematical or chemical notation
examples: In water's chemical formula H₂O the 2 is written as a subscript
Mathematical subscripts help distinguish between different variables in equations

definitions: arrangement to receive regular access to service publication or product for recurring payment
examples: Her streaming service subscription includes access to thousands of movies
The annual subscription saves money compared to buying individual issues

definitions: smaller division within section of document law or formal text
examples: Please refer to subsection 3.2 for detailed technical specifications
Each subsection of the contract addresses different legal obligations

definitions: sequence derived from another by deleting elements without changing remaining order
examples: The mathematical subsequence maintained the pattern of the original series
Each subsequence in the data showed similar growth trends

definitions: willingness to obey others unquestioningly often with loss of independence
examples: His subservience to his boss prevented him from expressing creative ideas
The culture promoted subservience rather than critical thinking

definitions: set whose elements are all contained within another larger set
examples: Teenagers are a subset of the total population being studied
This subset of data shows different patterns than the complete dataset

definitions: gradual sinking or settling of ground surface due to underground changes
examples: The subsidence caused cracks to appear in the building's foundation
Mining activities often lead to ground subsidence in surrounding areas

definitions: company controlled by another company through majority ownership of shares
examples: The corporation owns several subsidiaries in different countries
Each subsidiary operates independently but reports to the parent company

definitions: minimum resources needed to maintain life at basic survival level
examples: Many families struggle at subsistence level with barely enough to eat
Subsistence farming provides just enough food for the family's needs

definitions: layer of soil beneath topsoil containing less organic matter and nutrients
examples: The subsoil proved too rocky for planting deep-rooted trees
Engineers tested the subsoil before approving the building foundation

definitions: space that is contained within another space maintaining same mathematical properties
examples: The vector subspace contains all linear combinations of the basis vectors
Every plane through the origin forms a subspace in three dimensions

definitions: taxonomic category below species level showing distinct but not separate characteristics
examples: The tiger has several subspecies adapted to different geographical regions
This subspecies of butterfly is found only in tropical rainforests

definitions: facility in electrical grid that transforms voltage levels and distributes power
examples: The electrical substation serves power to the entire neighborhood
Lightning struck the substation causing widespread power outages

definitions: person or thing acting or serving in place of another
examples: The teacher called in a substitute when she fell ill
Honey makes a good substitute for sugar in many recipes

definitions: process of putting one person or thing in place of another
examples: Substituting olive oil for butter makes the recipe healthier
The coach kept substituting players to keep them fresh

definitions: act of replacing one thing or person with another serving same purpose
examples: The substitution of artificial sweeteners reduced the product's calorie content
Player substitution must follow the league's official rules

definitions: surface or material on which organism grows or is attached
substance on which enzyme acts in biochemical reaction
examples: The coral needs a hard substrate to attach and grow properly
Different plants require different soil substrates for optimal growth
The enzyme binds to its substrate to catalyze the chemical reaction
Researchers tested how different substrates affected the reaction rate

definitions: underlying layer or substance forming foundation or basis of something
examples: The cultural substratum of ancient civilizations still influences modern society
Geologists studied the rock substratum beneath the proposed building site

definitions: underlying structure or foundation that supports something built above it
examples: The bridge's substructure must withstand earthquakes and heavy traffic
Engineers reinforced the building's substructure before adding more floors

definitions: self-contained system within larger system performing specific function
examples: The cooling subsystem prevents the computer from overheating during operation
Each subsystem in the spacecraft has backup components for safety

definitions: deceit used to achieve goal or escape from difficult situation
examples: He used subterfuge to avoid answering the uncomfortable questions directly
The spy's subterfuge allowed her to gather information undetected

definitions: secondary title providing additional information about main title
text displayed on screen translating or transcribing spoken dialogue
examples: The book's subtitle explains the main topic in more detail
The article's subtitle summarized the key findings of the research
Foreign films often include subtitles for international audiences
The subtitles helped deaf viewers follow the movie's dialogue

definitions: quality of being delicate precise or difficult to analyze or describe
examples: The subtlety of her argument was lost on the impatient audience
Great actors convey emotion through subtlety rather than exaggeration

definitions: mathematical operation of taking one number or quantity away from another
examples: Children learn subtraction after mastering basic addition skills
The subtraction of expenses from revenue determines the company's profit

definitions: single part that combines with others to form larger functional unit
examples: Each protein subunit must fold correctly for the enzyme to function
The research team divided into subunits to tackle different problems

definitions: suburbs collectively especially characterized by middle-class residential uniformity and lifestyle
examples: They moved from the city to suburbia for better schools
Life in suburbia offered quiet streets and larger houses

definitions: systematic attempt to overthrow or undermine government or political system
examples: The government accused the group of subversion and arrested its leaders
Cultural subversion through art challenged the established social order
